{"id":"calc1_trig_001","course":"calc1","topic":"trig_derivatives","method":"trig_derivatives","template":"Differentiate f(x) = {a}sin(x) + cos({b}x).","variables":{"a":{"type":"int","range":[1,5],"step":1},"b":{"type":"int","range":[2,5],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"a*cos(x)-b*sin(b*x)","answerNorm":"a*cos(x)-b*sin(b*x)","solution_steps":[{"label":"Differentiate first term","math":"\\frac{d}{dx}[{a} \\sin(x)] = {a} \\cos(x)","note":""},{"label":"Differentiate second term","math":"\\frac{d}{dx}[\\cos({b}x)] = -{b} \\sin({b}x)","note":"Chain rule with inner {b}x"},{"label":"Combine","math":"f'(x) = {a} \\cos(x) - {b} \\sin({b}x)","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"physics","narrative":"An electromagnetic wave is modeled by E(x) = {a}sin(x) + cos({b}x) kV/m. Find dE/dx."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"chain_rule_trig","backwards_prompt":"d/dx[cos({b}x)] = -{b}sin({b}x) by chain rule. Show the steps.","break_errors":[{"type":"forgot_chain_rule","explanation":"Wrote derivative of cos({b}x) as -sin({b}x) instead of -{b}sin({b}x)."}],"tags":["derivatives","trigonometric","chain_rule"],"difficulty":1}
{"id":"calc1_trig_002","course":"calc1","topic":"trig_limits","method":"trig_limits","template":"Find lim_{x→0} (sin({a}x) - {a}x)/x³.","variables":{"a":{"type":"int","range":[1,4],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"-a**3/6","answerNorm":"-a^3/6","solution_steps":[{"label":"Use Taylor expansion","math":"\\sin(u) = u - u^3/6 + O(u^5)","note":""},{"label":"Substitute u = {a}x","math":"\\sin({a}x) = {a}x - ({a}x)^3/6 + O(x^5) = {a}x - {a}^3 x^3/6 + O(x^5)","note":""},{"label":"Compute numerator","math":"\\sin({a}x) - {a}x = -{a}^3 x^3/6 + O(x^5)","note":""},{"label":"Divide by x³","math":"\\frac{-{a}^3 x^3/6 + O(x^5)}{x^3} = -{a}^3/6 + O(x^2)","note":""},{"label":"Take limit","math":"\\lim_{x \\to 0} = -{a}^3/6","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"optics","narrative":"Diffraction pattern intensity involves lim_{x→0}(sin({a}x)-{a}x)/x³. Find the value."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"taylor_expansion","backwards_prompt":"sin(u) = u - u³/6 + O(u⁵). For u = {a}x, what is sin({a}x) - {a}x up to x³ terms?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_order_approximation","explanation":"Used sin(x) ≈ x - x³/6 but forgot to apply the {a} factor to the x³ term."}],"tags":["limits","trigonometric","taylor_series"],"difficulty":3}
{"id":"calc1_trig_003","course":"calc1","topic":"trig_integration","method":"trig_integration","template":"Evaluate ∫ sin²(x) dx.","variables":{},"answer_fn":"x/2-sin(2*x)/4","answerNorm":"x/2-sin(2*x)/4+C","solution_steps":[{"label":"Use power reduction","math":"\\sin^2(x) = \\frac{1 - \\cos(2x)}{2}","note":""},{"label":"Rewrite integral","math":"\\int \\sin^2(x) \\, dx = \\int \\frac{1 - \\cos(2x)}{2} \\, dx = \\frac{1}{2} \\int 1 \\, dx - \\frac{1}{2} \\int \\cos(2x) \\, dx","note":""},{"label":"Integrate","math":"= \\frac{x}{2} - \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{\\sin(2x)}{2} + C","note":"∫cos(2x)dx = sin(2x)/2"},{"label":"Simplify","math":"= \\frac{x}{2} - \\frac{\\sin(2x)}{4} + C","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"physics","narrative":"The average power in an AC circuit involves ∫ sin²(x) dx. Find the anti-derivative."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"power_reduction","backwards_prompt":"What trig identity converts sin²(x) into a form that can be integrated directly?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_identity","explanation":"Used sin²(x) = 1 - cos²(x) which doesn't help, instead of 1-cos(2x)/2."}],"tags":["integration","trigonometric","power_reduction"],"difficulty":2}
{"id":"calc1_log_001","course":"calc1","topic":"logarithms","method":"logarithm_properties","template":"Simplify ln({a}) + 2ln({b}) - ln({c}).","variables":{"a":{"type":"int","range":[2,10],"step":1},"b":{"type":"int","range":[2,10],"step":1},"c":{"type":"int","range":[2,10],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"log(a*b**2/c)","answerNorm":"ln(a*b^2/c)","solution_steps":[{"label":"Apply power rule to 2ln(b)","math":"2 \\ln({b}) = \\ln({b}^2)","note":""},{"label":"Apply quotient rule","math":"\\ln({a}) + \\ln({b}^2) - \\ln({c}) = \\ln\\left(\\frac{{{a} \\cdot {b}^2}{{{c}}}\\right)","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"chemistry","narrative":"Combine enthalpy changes: ΔG = ln({a}) + 2ln({b}) - ln({c}) kJ/mol. Simplify."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"logarithm_rules","backwards_prompt":"What are the three key logarithm rules being applied here: product, quotient, and power?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_log_rule","explanation":"Wrote ln(a) + 2ln(b) = 2ln(ab) instead of ln(a) + ln(b²) = ln(ab²)."}],"tags":["logarithms","properties","simplification"],"difficulty":1}
{"id":"calc1_log_002","course":"calc1","topic":"log_derivatives","method":"logarithmic_differentiation","template":"Find d/dx[log₁₀(x² + {a})].","variables":{"a":{"type":"int","range":[1,8],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"2*x/((x**2+a)*log(10))","answerNorm":"2*x/((x^2+a)*ln(10))","solution_steps":[{"label":"Recall derivative of log₁₀","math":"\\frac{d}{dx}[\\log_{10}(u)] = \\frac{1}{u \\ln(10)} \\frac{du}{dx}","note":"Change of base formula"},{"label":"Identify u","math":"u = x^2 + {a}, \\quad \\frac{du}{dx} = 2x","note":""},{"label":"Apply chain rule","math":"\\frac{d}{dx}[\\log_{10}(x^2 + {a})] = \\frac{1}{(x^2 + {a}) \\ln(10)} \\cdot 2x","note":""},{"label":"Simplify","math":"= \\frac{2x}{({x^2 + {a}) \\ln(10)}","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"signal_processing","narrative":"A signal amplitude in decibels uses dB(x) = 10·log₁₀(x²+{a}). Find the derivative."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"log_base_change","backwards_prompt":"d/dx[log₁₀(u)] = u'/(u·ln(10)). For u = x²+{a}, what is u'?","break_errors":[{"type":"forgot_ln","explanation":"Used derivative of ln(u) = u'/u instead of log₁₀(u) = u'/(u·ln(10))."}],"tags":["derivatives","logarithmic","base_10"],"difficulty":2}
{"id":"calc1_exp_001","course":"calc1","topic":"exponential","method":"exponential_growth","template":"A population of bacteria triples every {hours} hours. If the initial population is {initial}, what will it be after {t} hours?","variables":{"hours":{"type":"int","range":[2,5],"step":1},"initial":{"type":"int","range":[100,1000],"step":100},"t":{"type":"int","range":[1,10],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"initial*3**(t/hours)","answerNorm":"initial*3^(t/hours)","solution_steps":[{"label":"Growth model","math":"P(t) = P_0 \\cdot 3^{t/{hours}}","note":"Tripling means base = 3"},{"label":"Substitute values","math":"P({t}) = {initial} \\cdot 3^{{{t}/{hours}}}","note":""},{"label":"Compute exponent","math":"{t}/{hours} = {t/hours:.1f}","note":""},{"label":"Calculate population","math":"P({t}) = {initial} \\cdot 3^{{{t/hours:.1f}}} \\approx {int(initial*3**(t/hours))}","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"biology","narrative":"A bacterial culture triples every {hours} hours. Starting with {initial} colonies, how many after {t} hours?"}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"exponential_growth_formula","backwards_prompt":"For tripling every T hours, P(t) = P₀ · 3^(t/T). With P₀={initial}, T={hours}, t={t}, what is P({t})?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_exponent","explanation":"Used 3^(t·hours) instead of 3^(t/hours) for the growth factor."}],"tags":["exponential","growth","population","applications"],"difficulty":1}
{"id":"calc1_exp_002","course":"calc1","topic":"exponential","method":"compound_interest","template":"${initial} is invested at {rate}% annual interest, compounded monthly. How much after {years} years?","variables":{"initial":{"type":"int","range":[1000,10000],"step":1000},"rate":{"type":"float","range":[2,8],"step":0.5},"years":{"type":"int","range":[1,10],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"initial*(1+rate/1200)**(years*12)","answerNorm":"initial*(1+rate/1200)^(years*12)","solution_steps":[{"label":"Identify variables","math":"P = {initial}, \\quad r = {rate}/100, \\quad n = 12 \\text{{ (monthly)}}, \\quad t = {years}","note":""},{"label":"Compound interest formula","math":"A = P\\left(1 + \\frac{r}{n}\\right)^{nt}","note":""},{"label":"Substitute","math":"A = {initial}\\left(1 + \\frac{{{rate}/100}}{12}\\right)^{12 \\cdot {years}}","note":""},{"label":"Compute","math":"= {initial}\\left(1 + \\frac{{{rate}}}{{1200}}\\right)^{{{years*12}}} \\approx \\${initial * (1 + rate/1200)**(years*12):.2f}","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"finance","narrative":"A savings account with ${initial} earns {rate}% APY compounded monthly. Balance after {years} years?"}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"compound_formula","backwards_prompt":"A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt). For P={initial}, r={rate}%, n=12, t={years}, what is A?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_compounding_frequency","explanation":"Used n=1 (annual) instead of n=12 (monthly) for the compounding frequency."}],"tags":["exponential","compound_interest","finance","applications"],"difficulty":2}
{"id":"calc1_exp_003","course":"calc1","topic":"derivatives","method":"exp_derivatives","template":"Find d/dx[{a}^{x²}].","variables":{"a":{"type":"int","range":[2,5],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"2*x*ln(a)*a**(x**2)","answerNorm":"2*x*ln(a)*a^(x^2)","solution_steps":[{"label":"Use a^x = e^{x ln(a)}","math":"{a}^{x^2} = e^{x^2 \\ln({a})}","note":""},{"label":"Differentiate","math":"\\frac{d}{dx}[e^{x^2 \\ln({a})}] = e^{x^2 \\ln({a})} \\cdot 2x \\ln({a})","note":"Chain rule"},{"label":"Back-substitute","math":"= {a}^{x^2} \\cdot 2x \\ln({a})","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"physics","narrative":"A radioactive decay rate follows R(x) = {a}^{x²}. Find dR/dx."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"exponential_chain_rule","backwards_prompt":"d/dx[a^{g(x)}] = a^{g(x)} · ln(a) · g'(x). For g(x) = x², what is g'(x)?","break_errors":[{"type":"forgot_ln_a","explanation":"Wrote derivative as x²·{a}^{x²-1} instead of 2x·ln({a})·{a}^{x²}."}],"tags":["derivatives","exponential","chain_rule"],"difficulty":2}
{"id":"calc1_opt_005","course":"calc1","topic":"optimization","method":"second_derivative_test","template":"Find the local maximum and minimum of f(x) = x³ - 3x² - 9x + {c}.","variables":{"c":{"type":"int","range":[-5,10],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"local_max=-1,local_min=3","answerNorm":"max=-1,min=3","solution_steps":[{"label":"First derivative","math":"f'(x) = 3x^2 - 6x - 9 = 3(x^2 - 2x - 3) = 3(x+1)(x-3)","note":""},{"label":"Critical points","math":"f'(x) = 0 \\implies x = -1, x = 3","note":""},{"label":"Second derivative","math":"f''(x) = 6x - 6","note":""},{"label":"Test x = -1","math":"f''(-1) = -12 < 0 \\implies \\text{local maximum at } x = -1","note":""},{"label":"Test x = 3","math":"f''(3) = 12 > 0 \\implies \\text{local minimum at } x = 3","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"physics","narrative":"A particle's position is s(x) = x³ - 3x² - 9x + {c}. Find when velocity is max/min."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"second_derivative_classification","backwards_prompt":"f'(x) = 3(x+1)(x-3). What are the critical points and which is max vs min by the second derivative test?","break_errors":[{"type":"wrong_sign_test","explanation":"Used f''(x) > 0 for maximum instead of f''(x) < 0."}],"tags":["optimization","maxima","minima","second_derivative_test"],"difficulty":2}
{"id":"calc1_opt_006","course":"calc1","topic":"optimization","method":"closed_interval","template":"Find the absolute max and min of f(x) = x⁴ - 8x² + {c} on [{neg}, {pos}].","variables":{"c":{"type":"int","range":[0,10],"step":1},"neg":{"type":"int","range":[-3,-1],"step":1},"pos":{"type":"int","range":[1,3],"step":1}},"answer_fn":"max_at_0,min_at_boundary_or_crit","answerNorm":"abs_max,abs_min","solution_steps":[{"label":"Find critical points","math":"f'(x) = 4x^3 - 16x = 4x(x^2 - 4) = 4x(x-2)(x+2)","note":""},{"label":"Critical points in [neg, pos]","math":"x = 0 \\in [{neg}, {pos}]","note":"x = -2 not in interval if neg > -3"},{"label":"Evaluate at endpoints","math":"f({neg}) = {neg**4 - 8*neg**2 + c}, \\quad f({pos}) = {pos**4 - 8*pos**2 + c}","note":""},{"label":"Evaluate at critical point","math":"f(0) = {c}","note":""},{"label":"Compare","math":"\\text{Absolute max: } \\max(f({neg}), f(0), f({pos})); \\quad \\text{{Abs min: }} \\min(...)","note":""}],"contexts":[{"skin":"physics","narrative":"A particle's potential energy is U(x) = x⁴ - 8x² + {c} on the interval [{neg}, {pos}]. Find max/min potential."}],"modes_available":["solve","justify","backwards","break"],"justify_foil":"closed_interval_test","backwards_prompt":"For absolute extrema on [a,b], what points must you check?","break_errors":[{"type":"forgot_endpoints","explanation":"Found critical points but forgot to evaluate at the interval endpoints [{neg}, {pos}]."}],"tags":["optimization","absolute_extrema","closed_interval","critical_points"],"difficulty":2}